I loved this game - but I hate some details. In short: I would absolutely recommend it to everyone who likes the genre ("survival") AND strategic gameplay (making decisions that will have consequences, good or bad) WITH managing a team of survivors WITH role playing character development PLUS tactical turn based combat.  Not so short: I omit all my praises for the game (gameplay, graphics, ..., great game, love) here. What I hate about it is:  1. The tutorial/prologue is OK, but it does NOT make clear how important it is to ALWAYS have enough FOOD (reserves) as well as TOOLS. Run out of food = no guards on job. After the first some days, having no guards means running at risk that the undead will invade your camp and kill (eat up) one of your survivors (accept it, live with it - or, as I did at that point, start all over from the beginning). Every other job, except hunter, requires an EXTRA food ration per character. Hunter requires a tool per hunter. No tools = no hunting = no food. "Die, die, die my darling, ...". I agree with things (bad resource management, here) having consequences. But, if so, a game should make clear the vital game mechanics plus what happens, if you mess up with them. Dead Age does not do this. It's up to you to find out the hard way and throw hours of playtime into the void. I call it "stupid by design". Stupid, because it makes players hate your game and even might brake the game for some of them. By design, because it's not a tiny detail that has been overlooked - it's a vital fact that has not been pointed out and discussed in sufficient detail.  2. At a point in the last quarter of the game (story) you will have to make a decision on whom of the survivors is responsible for attacking another survivor, trying to kill him/her. All you get, is the question aside some bla bla that doesen't help at all. Unfortunately, you have no idea how important an otherwise trivial event (argument between two survivors) some days before would be (later). So, will you remember this one person out of 11 survivors by the time you are challenged to make that decision? I didn't. I came up to 2 potential candidates. Bad luck for me, I chose the wrong one. Means, you will loose the one survivor you (rightfully/wrongly) accused for having committed the crime plus one more, when the assassin strikes again some days later (provided you didn't choose the right one, before). Plus, of course, the assassin itself. Again, stupid by design. If game breaking "things" occur, fix them and fix them fast and once for all. This game is out long enough for such unnecessary stupid things to have been fixed. Should be, it is.  3. After completing the game for the first time, I spent all the medals earned into upgrades, chose the "engineer" career option and started anew. I checked my character and found  some of the bonuses promised for spending medals, were not there. I quit back to the main menu and - as you do not get multiple game saves per game run, just one and it is always the last state of things, so no turning back the time wheel whatsoever - then I decided to delete the game save ("profile"). BAD IDEA! Two clicks later, my complete game experience was gone, including each and everything, the medals too. Same as starting the newly installed game for the fist time. I overlooked the comment in the dialogue box asking if I really wanted to delete, saying "... and all your game progress including medals, too". No nothing that would catch your attention. Just a trivial comment in small letters of the same color as the rest of the text!!! Of course, no way to undelete (hint: it's called a trash can, but how should a pro game dev company know?) Really, by all and each and every hell in the multiverse - who is the quality assurance in charge at Headup Games. I WANT TO KILL HIM/HER. KILL IT DEAD. DEAD. DEAD AGE. For the concerned guys at Google: I was just making fun. I do not want and will not kill anybody, not in real life and not even in Dead Age. Not anymore. Unfortunately. Sadly. I'm done. GAME OVER.
